## Idea

In the context of [[Goodwillie calculus]], an [[(âˆž,1)-category]] is called _differentiable_ if [[(âˆž,1)-functors]] to it admit "derivatives" in the form of [[n-excisive approximations]].

## Definition

+-- {: .num_defn }
###### Definition

An [[(âˆž,1)-category]] $\mathcal{C}$ is **differentiable** if

1. it has [[finite (âˆž,1)-limits]];

1. it has [[sequential limit|sequential]] [[(âˆž,1)-colimits]];

1. the [[(âˆž,1)-colimit]] [[(âˆž,1)-functor]] $\underset{\longrightarrow}{\lim} Func(\mathbb{N}, \mathcal{C}) \longrightarrow \mathcal{C}$ is a [[left exact (âˆž,1)-functor]], hence commutes with [[finite (âˆž,1)-limits]].

=--

## Examples

+-- {: .num_example }
###### Example

Every [[(âˆž,1)-topos]] is a differentiable $(\infty,1)$-category.

=--

([Lurie, example 7.1.1.8](#Lurie))

## Properties

### $n$-Excisive reflection / Taylor tower

By [[Goodwillie calculus]], [[(âˆž,1)-functors]] to differentiable $(\infty,1)$-categories have [[n-excisive approximations]]/[[Taylor towers]].

